WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.840 --> 00:00:03.930
- I remember one time coming
out of a complex meeting

2
00:00:03.930 --> 00:00:06.720
that had a lot of action
items that I needed to capture

3
00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:09.210
and put into an email for the team.

4
00:00:09.210 --> 00:00:10.650
I was dreading it.

5
00:00:10.650 --> 00:00:12.750
And then I thought I should use AI

6
00:00:12.750 --> 00:00:14.610
for a first draft.

7
00:00:14.610 --> 00:00:15.480
It was great.

8
00:00:15.480 --> 00:00:17.910
I didn't have to worry about
capturing the action items.

9
00:00:17.910 --> 00:00:19.680
I didn't have to worry
about the formatting,

10
00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:21.660
and once I put my own touches

11
00:00:21.660 --> 00:00:24.390
and reviewed carefully
what AI had created,

12
00:00:24.390 --> 00:00:27.510
I sent off the email, and
it saved me a lot of time.

13
00:00:27.510 --> 00:00:30.300
AI can sometimes feel like magic.

14
00:00:30.300 --> 00:00:34.020
It is so much power to do
amazing things in seconds.

15
00:00:34.020 --> 00:00:36.690
When I get an impressive AI
result, I'm almost expecting

16
00:00:36.690 --> 00:00:38.550
to hear applause in the background,

17
00:00:38.550 --> 00:00:40.470
but of course, AI isn't magic.

18
00:00:40.470 --> 00:00:43.200
It's a computer program that,
like others, has capabilities

19
00:00:43.200 --> 00:00:44.580
and limitations.

20
00:00:44.580 --> 00:00:47.250
Understanding how AI
works can help you get

21
00:00:47.250 --> 00:00:48.213
the most out of it.

22
00:00:49.050 --> 00:00:51.000
I'm gonna walk you through
the top things you need

23
00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:53.280
to know about AI, and don't worry,

24
00:00:53.280 --> 00:00:55.680
I'll do without all the tech jargon.

25
00:00:55.680 --> 00:00:56.910
First things first.

26
00:00:56.910 --> 00:00:58.620
Let's get on the same page.

27
00:00:58.620 --> 00:00:59.820
When we say AI,

28
00:00:59.820 --> 00:01:02.940
what are we really talking
about beyond the buzzword?

29
00:01:02.940 --> 00:01:05.490
You probably already know that AI stands

30
00:01:05.490 --> 00:01:08.250
for artificial intelligence.

31
00:01:08.250 --> 00:01:10.110
Artificial intelligence is the concept

32
00:01:10.110 --> 00:01:11.940
of building intelligent machines

33
00:01:11.940 --> 00:01:14.160
that can do things like
reasoning through a problem

34
00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:16.410
and providing recommendations.

35
00:01:16.410 --> 00:01:18.180
But how does it do that?

36
00:01:18.180 --> 00:01:20.340
Well, within the world of AI,

37
00:01:20.340 --> 00:01:22.980
you have something called models.

38
00:01:22.980 --> 00:01:25.740
AI models are computer programs
that are trained on tons

39
00:01:25.740 --> 00:01:28.710
of data, like articles, images, or videos.

40
00:01:28.710 --> 00:01:30.840
The model finds patterns in the data,

41
00:01:30.840 --> 00:01:33.270
and then is able to apply those patterns

42
00:01:33.270 --> 00:01:35.880
to new situations like making predictions

43
00:01:35.880 --> 00:01:37.740
or generating new content.

44
00:01:37.740 --> 00:01:39.600
This process, called training,

45
00:01:39.600 --> 00:01:41.643
helps the model improve over time,

46
00:01:42.540 --> 00:01:45.630
and this isn't some futuristic technology.

47
00:01:45.630 --> 00:01:47.700
Think of your email spam filter.

48
00:01:47.700 --> 00:01:49.440
It uses massive amounts of data

49
00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:50.790
to help sort emails you want

50
00:01:50.790 --> 00:01:53.970
from the emails you don't
want, you know, spam.

51
00:01:53.970 --> 00:01:56.010
Every time you mark something as spam,

52
00:01:56.010 --> 00:01:59.100
it learns from that and gets
better and better over time.

53
00:01:59.100 --> 00:02:01.800
But what happens when your
spam filter gets it wrong

54
00:02:01.800 --> 00:02:04.320
and an important email gets lost?

55
00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:07.413
The answer may lie in the
model's training data.

56
00:02:08.370 --> 00:02:11.370
This is the data that AI learns from.

57
00:02:11.370 --> 00:02:13.410
Let's look at another example.

58
00:02:13.410 --> 00:02:15.810
Say, a food distributor trains an AI model

59
00:02:15.810 --> 00:02:17.523
to sort apples from other fruit.

60
00:02:18.390 --> 00:02:21.540
This model's training data
includes thousands of images

61
00:02:21.540 --> 00:02:25.650
of apples, enabling the model
to recognize, well, apples.

62
00:02:25.650 --> 00:02:27.360
But what happens if the training data

63
00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:30.540
only included images of red apples?

64
00:02:30.540 --> 00:02:33.330
This might make the model
less accurate at identifying

65
00:02:33.330 --> 00:02:36.330
other types of apples,
like green or yellow.

66
00:02:36.330 --> 00:02:38.100
As a result, the food distributor

67
00:02:38.100 --> 00:02:39.870
might end up sorting apples incorrectly,

68
00:02:39.870 --> 00:02:41.130
causing them to lose money

69
00:02:41.130 --> 00:02:43.530
and waste perfectly good apples.

70
00:02:43.530 --> 00:02:46.350
A model's training data
shapes what it does.

71
00:02:46.350 --> 00:02:49.140
It's also one reason why
one model may produce

72
00:02:49.140 --> 00:02:50.940
different results from another.

73
00:02:50.940 --> 00:02:53.610
A second reason is the
model architecture itself.

74
00:02:53.610 --> 00:02:54.900
How a model is programmed

75
00:02:54.900 --> 00:02:56.520
and the rules it applies to its data

76
00:02:56.520 --> 00:02:59.100
and learning may vary from model to model.

77
00:02:59.100 --> 00:03:02.550
Some AI models, like Gemini,
learn from massive amounts

78
00:03:02.550 --> 00:03:05.940
of data that go way beyond
images of fruit alone.

79
00:03:05.940 --> 00:03:07.590
With more data and training,

80
00:03:07.590 --> 00:03:10.500
a model can start doing
some pretty amazing things.

81
00:03:10.500 --> 00:03:11.820
It can understand a request

82
00:03:11.820 --> 00:03:13.110
and respond to it,

83
00:03:13.110 --> 00:03:15.000
even if it's the first
time it's encountering

84
00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:16.233
that type of request.

85
00:03:17.100 --> 00:03:21.660
This advanced type of model is
called a large language model

86
00:03:21.660 --> 00:03:23.730
or an LLM for short.

87
00:03:23.730 --> 00:03:25.260
LLMs can learn so much

88
00:03:25.260 --> 00:03:27.420
and get so good at
predicting based on patterns

89
00:03:27.420 --> 00:03:29.670
that they can create entirely new content

90
00:03:29.670 --> 00:03:32.970
like blog posts or birthday haiku.

91
00:03:32.970 --> 00:03:36.780
AI's ability to create something
new is called Generative AI

92
00:03:36.780 --> 00:03:38.343
or GenAI for short.

93
00:03:39.240 --> 00:03:41.010
It gets even more amazing.

94
00:03:41.010 --> 00:03:44.370
Some GenAI assistants are multimodal,

95
00:03:44.370 --> 00:03:46.740
which is just a fancy way
of saying they can work

96
00:03:46.740 --> 00:03:48.300
with more than just text.

97
00:03:48.300 --> 00:03:51.330
They can understand and
create images, videos,

98
00:03:51.330 --> 00:03:53.130
audio, and more.

99
00:03:53.130 --> 00:03:55.590
So you could upload a photo of a chart

100
00:03:55.590 --> 00:03:57.420
and ask for a text summary of it

101
00:03:57.420 --> 00:04:00.150
or submit an audio recording of a meeting

102
00:04:00.150 --> 00:04:02.700
and have it turned into
a list of action items.

103
00:04:02.700 --> 00:04:05.400
Or you could easily
create compelling visuals

104
00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:07.770
for your website or client presentation.

105
00:04:07.770 --> 00:04:10.500
Let's look at another way AI is evolving.

106
00:04:10.500 --> 00:04:14.280
You may have heard about AI Agents.

107
00:04:14.280 --> 00:04:16.050
What's that all about?

108
00:04:16.050 --> 00:04:18.240
Well, think of agents as systems

109
00:04:18.240 --> 00:04:21.180
that combine the intelligence
of advanced AI models

110
00:04:21.180 --> 00:04:24.360
with access to tools like
your calendar or email.

111
00:04:24.360 --> 00:04:27.060
Instead of giving an agent a single task,

112
00:04:27.060 --> 00:04:28.710
you can give it a broader goal.

113
00:04:28.710 --> 00:04:31.440
Then the agent can break that
goal down into smaller steps

114
00:04:31.440 --> 00:04:34.890
and take action on your
behalf, all under your control.

115
00:04:34.890 --> 00:04:37.477
For example, imagine telling an AI agent,

116
00:04:37.477 --> 00:04:40.470
"Organize a kickoff meeting
for the Q3 marketing project

117
00:04:40.470 --> 00:04:43.830
with the design and sales
teams for next week."

118
00:04:43.830 --> 00:04:46.740
An AI agent could then
check everyone's calendars

119
00:04:46.740 --> 00:04:48.030
for a free slot,

120
00:04:48.030 --> 00:04:50.220
book a meeting room, draft a welcome email

121
00:04:50.220 --> 00:04:51.660
with the project brief attached,

122
00:04:51.660 --> 00:04:53.643
and send out the calendar invitation.

123
00:04:54.570 --> 00:04:57.450
It can handle all the tedious
coordination, freeing the team

124
00:04:57.450 --> 00:05:00.360
to focus on the actual
strategy for the meeting.

125
00:05:00.360 --> 00:05:02.970
The opportunity there is not
just answering your questions,

126
00:05:02.970 --> 00:05:06.210
but actively helping you
to accomplish your goals.

127
00:05:06.210 --> 00:05:09.420
Okay, great, we've talked
about what AI is, how it works,

128
00:05:09.420 --> 00:05:11.340
and some emerging capabilities.

129
00:05:11.340 --> 00:05:13.890
This is crucial for you
to be an informed user.

130
00:05:13.890 --> 00:05:15.030
It allows you to make the most

131
00:05:15.030 --> 00:05:18.480
of AI's possibilities while
understanding its limitations.

132
00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:19.563
Let's keep going.